      <!-- Part 5: Quick Reference Cheat Sheet -->
      <div class="cheat-sheet fade-in">
        <h3>Quick-reference cheat sheet</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Let it interview you</strong> — For complex or context-heavy prompts, ask Copilot to pose 5 clarifying questions before it answers. Answering them sharpens the goal and produces a far better result.</li>
          <li><strong>Break it down</strong> — Multi-step prompts beat single complex ones. Review and refine between steps.</li>
          <li><strong>Assign a persona</strong> — "Act as a..." instantly sets expertise level and tone.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask what it needs</strong> — When stuck, ask Copilot what context would help most.</li>
          <li><strong>Think end-to-end</strong> — Don't just create a table of action items; write the whole follow-up email that includes the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Experiment</strong> — Try different structures, tones, and follow-ups. Curiosity reveals new capability.</li>
          <li><strong>Iterate always</strong> — Your first result is a draft, not a final answer. Refine, adjust, repeat.</li>
